### File Structure
```
OnlineLibrary/
│
├── app.py
├── requirements.txt
├── README.md
│
├── templates/
│   ├── dashboard.html
│   ├── book_catalog.html
│   ├── book_details.html
│   ├── borrow_confirmation.html
│   ├── my_borrowings.html
│   ├── my_reservations.html
│   ├── my_reviews.html
│   ├── write_review.html
│   ├── user_profile.html
│   └── payment_confirmation.html
│
├── static/
│   ├── css/
│   │   └── styles.css
│   ├── js/
│   │   └── scripts.js
│   └── images/
│       └── (book covers and other images)
│
└── data/
    ├── users.txt
    ├── books.txt
    ├── borrowings.txt
    ├── reservations.txt
    ├── reviews.txt
    └── fines.txt
```

### File Descriptions
- **app.py**  
  The main backend Python application file. It will use a web framework like Flask to handle routing, page rendering, and business logic. This file manages all interactions with the local text files in the `data/` directory, including reading, writing, and updating user, book, borrowing, reservation, review, and fine data. Since the application is not very complex, consolidating backend logic into this single file simplifies maintenance and deployment.

- **requirements.txt**  
  Lists Python dependencies required to run the application (e.g., Flask).

- **README.md**  
  Documentation for setup, running the app, and any other relevant notes.

- **templates/**  
  Contains all HTML template files for the 10 pages specified in the requirements. Each HTML file corresponds to one page and includes the specified elements with their IDs for frontend rendering and interaction.

- **static/css/styles.css**  
  Stylesheet for the web application to ensure consistent and user-friendly UI design.

- **static/js/scripts.js**  
  JavaScript file to handle client-side interactivity such as button clicks, form validations, and dynamic content updates.

- **static/images/**  
  Folder to store book cover images and any other static images used in the UI.

- **data/**  
  Directory containing all the local text files used for data storage as per the specified formats:
  - `users.txt` — user information
  - `books.txt` — book details and status
  - `borrowings.txt` — borrowing records
  - `reservations.txt` — reservation records
  - `reviews.txt` — user reviews
  - `fines.txt` — fine records

This structure cleanly separates backend logic, frontend templates, static assets, and data storage, aligning well with the project requirements and ensuring maintainability and scalability.
